Gunnera tinctoria

   [6569.jpg]
   Authority (Molina) Mirbel
   Family Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Haloragidales:Gunneraceae
   Synonyms Gunnera scabra (Ruiz.&Pav.), Gunnera chilensis (Lam.), Panke
   tinctoria Molina
   Common names gunnera, Chilean rhubarb, Chilean gunnera, Chilean
   'ape'ape, pangue, nalca, raway
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 6569

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: It is a perennial, herbaceous plant that looks like an
   overgrown rhubarb. In a sheltered positions and moist soils, the stem
   can be 1.5-2.5 m tall and the leaf up to 1 m across. USE: The young
   leaf stalks are edible; a black dye is obtained from the root; the root
   contains 9% tannin; the whole plant has medicinal properties; a very
   ornamental plant with huge leaves, it forms a slowly reading dense
   clump that is quit striking, but needs space GROWING PERIOD: Perennial.
   COMMON NAMES: Gunnera, Chilean rhubarb, Chilean gunnera, Chilean
   'ape'ape. FURTHER INF: It can be found in moist soils by lakes,
   meadows, marshes, bog gardens, woodlands, sunny edges, dappled shades,
   streams and rivers. Plants can be grown in quite coarse grass, which
   can be cut annually in the autumn. It prefers a moist position in light
   shade sheltered from strong winds. It is native of Patagonia, Chile and
   found from southern Chile to Ecuador in western South America. It was
   introduced into England in 1849 and is now naturalized from cultivation
   in Europe.

   Sources
   http://www.ibiblio.org/pfaf/cgi-bin/arr_html?Gunnera+tinctoria

